Part I: Practice Questions

1. Prove the following statements:

  1. The sum of the \(y\) observations is the same as the sum of the fitted values. \[\begin{align*} \sum_i \hat{y_i} &= \sum_i \left(\hat{\beta}_0+ \hat{\beta}_1 x_i \right)\\ &= n \hat{\beta_0} + \hat{\beta}_1 n \bar{x}\\ &= n \left(\bar{y} - \hat{\beta_1} \bar{x} \right) + \hat{\beta}_1 n \bar{x} = n \bar{y} = \sum_i y_i \end{align*}\]

  2. The sum of the residuals weighted by the fitted values is zero.

    \[\begin{align*} \sum_i \hat{y_i} r_i &= \sum_i \left(\hat{\beta}_0+ \hat{\beta}_1 x_i \right) r_i\\ &= \hat{\beta_0} \sum r_i + \hat{\beta}_1 \sum_i x_i r_i = 0, \end{align*}\] since \(\sum r_i = 0\) and \(\sum_i x_i r_i = 0\).

  7. The manufacturer has suggested that the mean required time should not increase by more than 14 minutes for each additional copier that is serviced on a service call. Conduct a test to decide whether this standard is being Satisfied by Tri-City. Control the risk of a type I error at 0.05. State the alternatives, decision rule and conclusion.

    We want to test whether \(\beta_1>14\), so the alternatives are \[\begin{cases} &H_0: \beta_1 = 14\\ &H_{\alpha}: \beta_1 \geq 14 \end{cases}\] The test statistic is given by: \[t = \frac{\hat{\beta}_1 - 14}{sd_{\hat{\beta}_1}}\] 

    (summary(copier.reg)$coef[2,1]-14)/(summary(copier.reg)$coef[2,2])
    ## [1] 2.142984

    while the corresponding critical value of the T distribution is

    qt(0.95, df = copier.reg$df)
    ## [1] 1.681071

    So, the decision rule is: since 2.142984 \(>\) 1.681071, we reject the null and conclude that this standard is not being Satisfied by Tri-City.

Part II: HW Questions


1. SLR Reversed

Consider the Simple Linear Regression model as defined in class: \[y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i + \varepsilon_i \qquad \text{ (Model I)}\] where the \(\varepsilon\) random errors have mean zero, are homoscedastic and uncorrelated.

Now, assume that we interchange the response \(y_i\) with the predictor \(x_i\) and fit the following Simple Linear Regression model: \[x_i = b_0 + b_1 y_i + \varepsilon^*_i \qquad\text{(Model II)}\] where the \(\varepsilon^*\) random errors have mean zero, are homoscedastic and uncorrelated.

  1. Derive (i.e.show your work step-by-step) the Least-Squares estimators for \(b_0\) and \(b_1\).

    We minimize the Residual Sum of Squares (RSS): \[\text{RSS} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( x_i - \beta_0 - \beta_1 y_i \right)^2\]

    To find the solution and obtain \((\hat{\beta_0}, \hat{\beta_1})\), we have \[\begin{align*} \frac{\partial \text{RSS}}{\partial \beta_0} = 0 \,\,& \,\,\Leftrightarrow -2\sum_{i=1}^n \left( x_i - \beta_0 - \beta_1 y_i \right) =0 \\ \frac{\partial \text{RSS}}{\partial \beta_1} = 0 \,\, & \,\,\Leftrightarrow -2\sum_{i=1}^n \left(x_i - \beta_0 - \beta_1 y_i \right) y_i = 0 \end{align*}\]

    Re-arrange the equations to obtain \[\begin{align*} \beta_0 n + \beta_1 \sum_{i=1}^n y_i & = \sum_{i=1}^n x_i \\ \beta_0 \sum_{i=1}^n y_i + \beta_1 \sum_{i=1}^n y_i^2 & =\sum_{i=1}^n y_i x_i \end{align*}\] Then, solve the system with respect to \(\beta_0\), \(\beta_1\).

    \[\begin{align*} \hat{\beta_1} &= \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n (x_i - \bar{x})(y_i-\bar{y})}{\sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \bar{y})^2} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i y_i - n \bar{x} \bar{y}}{\sum_{i=1}^n y_i^2 - n \bar{y}^2}\\ \hat{\beta_0} &= \bar{x} - \hat{\beta_1} \bar{y}\\ \end{align*}\]

    In this problem, if one took Model I, solved with respect to \(x_i\) and then plugged-in the \(\hat{\beta}_0\), \(\hat{\beta}_1\) estimators to the new drift and new intercept coefficients, then that would be incorrect. These values would not be the LS estimators for Model II.


  2. Let \(R^2_I\) be the \(R^2\) of model I and \(R^2_{II}\) the \(R^2\) of model II. Are they the same or not? Discuss.

    The quick way to answer this question is to observe that \(R^2_{I} = r_{X,Y} = Corr(X,Y) = Corr(Y,X) = r_{YX} = R^2_{II}\).

    You can also try to take the definition of the Model I and II \(R^2\) based on the SS, but it will require quite a bit of calculations



Stat Grades

The StatGrades.csv data set contains 4 Quiz Scores and a Final Exam score from an Introductory Statistics course (actual course I taught several years ago!). Our goal in this example is to investigate if the average of the Quizzes can be used to explain the variation in the Final Exam scores by fitting a linear regression model of the Final Examscore vs.the Average Quiz score.

We start by importing the data to R: 

statgrades = read.csv('StatGrades.csv',header=TRUE)
dim(df)
## NULL
head(df)
##                                               
## 1 function (x, df1, df2, ncp, log = FALSE)    
## 2 {                                           
## 3     if (missing(ncp))                       
## 4         .Call(C_df, x, df1, df2, log)       
## 5     else .Call(C_dnf, x, df1, df2, ncp, log)
## 6 }

  1. Compute the new variable Quiz Average and add it to the data frame.

    # Calculate the quiz average of 4 quizzes and creating a new column in the data frame statgrades
statgrades$quiz_average = rowMeans(statgrades[,-5], na.rm = TRUE)
head(statgrades)


  2. Obtain the estimated regression line.

    grades.lm = lm(final ~ quiz_average, data = statgrades)
summary(grades.lm)
    ## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = final ~ quiz_average, data = statgrades)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -70.429  -6.011   1.050   8.201  27.189 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   3.94717    3.15490   1.251    0.212    
## quiz_average  0.85667    0.04164  20.572   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 12.84 on 380 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.5269, Adjusted R-squared:  0.5256 
## F-statistic: 423.2 on 1 and 380 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

    The fitted regression model we fitted is \[(Final) = 3.95\; + 0.86\; (Quiz \;Average)\] where \(\hat{\beta}_0=3.95\) and \(\hat{\beta}_1=0.86\). These can also be obtained by

    statgrades.coef = summary(grades.lm)$coef 
statgrades.coef
    ##               Estimate Std. Error   t value     Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)  3.9471722 3.15490202  1.251124 2.116591e-01
## quiz_average 0.8566662 0.04164323 20.571558 9.849190e-64


  3. Plot the estimated regression function and the data. How well does the estimated regression function fit the data?

    library(ggplot2)
scatterplot = ggplot(statgrades, aes(quiz_average, final)) +
geom_point(size=2, color='darkblue') +
labs(title="Final exam score vs. Average quiz score",y="Final exam score", 
x="Average quiz score") + theme(legend.position = "none") + theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) + geom_smooth(method=lm)
plot(scatterplot)
    ## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

    The regression line has a relatively good fit to the data. We see that there is a lot of variation of the points around the regression line. Our visual conclusion is also supported by the \(R^2\) value with is about 52/7%.

    We also observe some unusual observations in the plot - which we will discuss later on how to handle!


  4. Interpret \(\hat{\beta}_0\) in your estimated regression function. Does \(\hat{\beta}_0\) provide any relevant information here? Explain.

    In this case, \(\hat{\beta}_0 = 3.95\), which implies that a student with zero average quiz score would get 3.95 on the final? Well, the intercept in this case does not have a meaningful interpretation. The value zero was not in the observed data, so this extrapolation is not necessarily correct.

  9. Conduct an \(F\) test to determine whether or not there is a linear association between Final Exam score and Quiz Average. Use \(\alpha\) equal to 0.1. State the alternatives, decision rule and conclusion.

    The hypothesis we want to test is formulated as follows: \[\begin{cases} &H_0: \beta_1=0\\ &H_{\alpha}: \beta_1\neq 0\\ \end{cases} \]

    We can perform this test using the anova function in R:

     anova(grades.lm)
    Using the p-value, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the slope coefficient is a statistically significant and that there is a linear association between Final Exam score and Quiz Average.

    This is measured by \(R^2\)

    ## [1] 0.5268859
    Here, it is approximately 52.7% which is a medium-sized reduction.


  11. Calculate \(r\) (the correlation coefficient) and attach the appropriate sign.

    ## [1] 0.7258691
    The correct sign for the correlation coeffcient is the + sign, since this os the sign of the slope coefficient.
